      <h2>The Concept of Geographic Arbitrage</h2>
      <p>
        Arbitrage — exploiting price differences between markets — is typically the domain of traders and investors. Remote work has opened a version of this opportunity to anyone whose job can be done from a laptop.
      </p>
      <p>
        The opportunity exists because labor markets and housing markets operate on different geographies. Companies — especially in tech, finance, and professional services — pay salaries benchmarked to the local labor market where they're headquartered. A software engineer at a San Francisco company earns a San Francisco-calibrated salary. When that engineer works remotely from Knoxville, Tennessee, their income stays anchored to the San Francisco market while their expenditures drop to Knoxville levels.
      </p>
      <p>
        The BEA's Regional Price Parity data quantifies this gap precisely. San Francisco's metro area has an RPP of roughly 127; Knoxville's is roughly 88. The ratio (127 ÷ 88 = 1.44) represents the potential purchasing power multiplier from this arbitrage: $100,000 in nominal income buys $114,000 worth of national-average consumption in Knoxville vs. $78,700 in San Francisco. That's a 45% difference in actual living standard from the same nominal income.
      </p>

      <h2>Quantifying the Gain</h2>
      <p>
        The calculation is straightforward. Use the BEA's RPP for your current location and your target location:
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Real purchasing power = (Nominal salary ÷ Local RPP) × 100</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        If you earn $120,000 and relocate from a high-cost city (RPP 120) to a low-cost metro (RPP 88):
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Current real purchasing power: $120,000 ÷ 120 × 100 = <strong>$100,000</strong></li>
        <li>Post-move real purchasing power: $120,000 ÷ 88 × 100 = <strong>$136,364</strong></li>
        <li>Gain: $36,364 — a <strong>36.4% increase</strong> in what your money buys</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
