      </p>

      <h3>Southern Mid-Sized Cities</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Knoxville, TN</strong> — RPP approximately 88–90. University of Tennessee anchors a mid-sized city with a thriving downtown, outdoor access (Smoky Mountains), no state income tax on wages, and fiber internet widely available.</li>
        <li><strong>Huntsville, AL</strong> — RPP approximately 88–90. NASA and defense contractor presence means high local incomes but kept costs surprisingly moderate. Strong infrastructure, growing tech scene.</li>
        <li><strong>Chattanooga, TN</strong> — RPP approximately 89–92. Known for deploying one of the first municipal gigabit fiber networks in the US. Scenic location, affordable neighborhoods, no state income tax on wages.</li>
        <li><strong>Greenville-Spartanburg, SC</strong> — RPP approximately 89–92. Growing manufacturing and professional services hub; increasingly popular remote worker destination; attractive downtown revitalization.</li>
        <li><strong>Raleigh-Cary, NC</strong> — RPP approximately 95–99. Slightly higher costs than the above but access to a genuinely strong local tech job market (Research Triangle), major universities, and good infrastructure. Useful if you want optionality to take local work.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Midwest Options</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Columbus, OH</strong> — RPP approximately 93–96. Large Midwest metro with diverse economy, solid infrastructure, growing tech scene, and moderate housing costs. OSU research ecosystem provides cultural and intellectual amenities.</li>
        <li><strong>Indianapolis, IN</strong> — RPP approximately 90–94. Life sciences and tech employment base; housing well below national average; no mountains but good quality of life infrastructure.</li>
        <li><strong>Kansas City, MO-KS</strong> — RPP approximately 91–94. Straddling two states; arts scene, BBQ culture, affordable housing, and improving downtown districts. Google Fiber has excellent coverage in parts of the metro.</li>
        <li><strong>Madison, WI</strong> — RPP approximately 93–97. University town with high quality of life, educated workforce, strong coffee-shop-and-coworking culture for remote workers. Winters are a trade-off.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Mountain West</h3>
